Functional Requirements
REQ-01: Manage a Central Warehouse
Description: The system shall store and allow retrieval of the number of beverages stored (by type and predefined prices) and the number of stored empties in the central warehouse.
Priority: High
Actors: System

REQ-02: Manage Bars
Description: The system shall store and manage bar details including name/description, location, and the stock of different beverage types and predefined prices. 
Priority: High
Actors: System

REQ-03: Manage Bottle Drop Point
Description: The system shall store and manage details of bottle drop points, including location, capacity, and current stock of empties.
Priority: High
Actors: System

REQ-04: View Warehouse Data and Status
Description: Warehouse staff should be able to view up-to-date information about the warehouse, including the number of beverage types stored and the number of stored empties.
Priority: High
Actors: Warehouse Staff

REQ-05: View Bar Data and Status
Description: Bartenders should be able to access real-time information about their bar, including the stock levels of different beverage types.
Priority: High
Actors: Bartenders

REQ-06: Bars Request Automatic Stock Replenishment
Description: Bars should be able to automatically trigger stock replenishment requests from the warehouse when the quantity of any beverage type falls below a defined threshold.
Priority: High
Actors: System

REQ-07: Purchase Drinks at a Bar
Description: Visitors should be able to purchase available drinks at a bar, with the system updating the bar's beverage stock accordingly.
Priority: High
Actors: Visitors

REQ-08: Return Empty Bottles to a Bottle Drop Point
Description: Visitors should be able to return empty bottles at a designated bottle drop point, with the system recording the quantity of returned empties.
Priority: High
Actors: Visitors

REQ-09: Report a Full Bottle Drop Point
Description: Visitors should be able to report that a bottle drop point is full, enabling the system to flag it for maintenance or collection.
Priority: High
Actors: Visitors

REQ-10: View All Bottle Drop Points Data and Status
Description: Stockists should be able to view information about all bottle drop points, including their locations, capacities, and current stock of empties.
Priority: High
Actors: Stockists

REQ-11: Prevent Bottle Returns to Full Drop Points
Description: The system should prevent visitors from returning empty bottles to a bottle drop point that has reached its full capacity.
Priority: High
Actors: System
REQ-12: Empty Bottle Drop Points to Central Warehouse
Description: It should be possible to empty a bottle drop point by transferring the stored empties to the central warehouse, updating the inventories of both locations accordingly.
Priority: High
Actors: Stockists

REQ-13: Management Events
Description: Event planners should be able to create and configure events by specifying event details such as name, date, location, duration, and status. They should also be able to define the list of beverage types available for that event. Planners should be able to edit or delete the event as needed.
Priority: High
Actors: Planners

REQ-14: Set Up Bars with Location and Capacities, and Initial Stock
Description: Event planners should be able to configure bars for the event, specifying the number of bars, their locations, and per-drink storage capacities, and initial beverage stock for each drink type.
Priority: High
Actors: Planners

REQ-15: Set Up Bottle Drop Points with Location and Capacity
Description: Event planners should be able to configure bottle drop points, including the number needed, their locations, and the capacity (maximum number of empties they can hold).
Priority: High
Actors: Planners

REQ-16: Manage Users
Description: Admins should be able to register new users (e.g., bartenders, warehouse staff, stockists) and assign appropriate roles during the account creation process. Admins should be able to view, deactivate or delete user accounts when access is no longer required.
Priority: High
Actors: Admins (Planners)

REQ-17: User Login and Authentication
Description: All users must log in to access the system. The system shall verify user credentials and grant access based on authentication status.
Priority: High
Actors: All Users

REQ-18: Role-Based Authorization
Description: The system shall enforce role-based access control, ensuring users can only access functionalities permitted by their assigned roles (e.g., only planners can configure events).
Priority: High
Actors: System

REQ-19: Manage User Profile
Description: Users should be able to view and update their own profile information, such as name, email, and password.
Priority: Medium
Actors: All Users

REQ-20: Manage System Notifications
Description: The system shall automatically send notifications to the appropriate users when specific conditions occur, such as a bottle drop point being reported as full by a visitor, a bar requiring a refill, or other system-defined thresholds being met.
Priority: High
Actors: System


Description of the Domain Concepts (Domain Model)

Entities:


Bar: name, location, drinkStock
Drink: id, name, quantity
BottleDropPoint: id, location, capacity, currentLevel
Warehouse: id, drinkStock, emptyBottleStock
Order: id, visitorId, barId, drinkId, status
User: id, name, role

Relationships:

Bars stock multiple Drink types.
Visitors place Orders at Bars.
Drop Points belong to the event layout and collect empty bottles.
Warehouse manages both drink and empty bottle stock and coordinates with Bars and Drop Points.

A UML diagram will visualize these entities and their interrelations.
